title: Cofiniteness
summary: In mathematics, a cofinite subset of a set X {\displaystyle X} is a subset A {\displaystyle A} whose complement in X {\displaystyle X} is a finite set. In other words, A {\displaystyle A} contains all but finitely many elements of X . {\displaystyle X.} If the complement is not finite, but is countable, then one says the set is cocountable.
